    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-06-19T11:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-06-19T11:29:00-05:00" n="556"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d556">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/2084</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vologda</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-06-19T21:00:00+04:31">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 19, 1918, 9 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received June 21, 7.55 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>285. <persName>Vosnesenski</persName>, talkative chief of the Far Eastern
                    Division of Soviet Foreign Office, who represented Soviet government at
                        <persName corresp="#p_SM1">Summers</persName>’s funeral, called yesterday
                    saying would be in Vologda five or six days. If his visit had any object it was
                    to tell me that <persName corresp="#p_CGV1">Chicherin</persName> had instructed
                    him to say that notes demanding war vessels leave Russian ports<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d556fn3">See telegrams dated June 16 and June 21, <ref
                            target="frus1918Russiav02">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>
                        </ref>, chap. ii.</note> were sent to please the Germans or perhaps by
                    German orders and that <persName corresp="#p_CGV1">Chicherin</persName> expected
                    no reply or action thereon. <persName>Radek</persName> had told
                        <persName>Lehrs</persName>
                    <note n="4" xml:id="d556fn4">
                        <persName>John A. Lehrs</persName>, Vice Consul at Moscow.</note> the same
                    and <persName corresp="#p_PDC1">Poole</persName> had so wired me.</p>
                <p>Have heard from two sources that a German colonel in uniform had recently met
                    combination group in Moscow and promised that 10,000 Germans with German
                    division organized from prisoners of <pb facs="0638" n="564" xml:id="pg_564"/>
                    war would overturn Bolshevik government in one week, if combination group would
                    favor German alliance and compel Allied forces and Allied representatives to
                    leave Russia and that combination group considering proposition and disposed to
                    accept. …</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_FDR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
